G4.fix_sketch:
Rust-only minimal fix (Python already conforms). In crates/clankerprof-core/src/compare.rs, make summary_total preserve the JSON integer instead of coercing through i64:

fn summary_total(payload: &Value) -> Result<Value, String> {
    let Some(summary) = payload.get("summary") else {
        return Ok(json!(0));
    };
    if !summary.is_object() {
        return Err("Report summary must be an object.".to_string());
    }
    match summary.get("total_time_ns") {
        None => Ok(json!(0)),
        Some(value) if value.is_i64() || value.is_u64() => Ok(value.clone()),
        Some(_) => Err("Report summary field 'total_time_ns' must be an integer.".to_string()),
    }
}

Both call sites ("after_total_ns": summary_total(after)?, "before_total_ns": summary_total(before)? at compare.rs:164-165 and 406-407) already interpolate into json!, so returning Value compiles unchanged. serde_json serializes i64 and u64 as exact decimal integers, matching Python's exact int passthrough byte-for-byte across the full contract domain [i64::MIN, u64::MAX]; floats/bools/strings still hit the existing error (is_i64/is_u64 are false for them), preserving the error message and strict-rejection semantics. Out-of-contract integers beyond u64::MAX parse as f64 in serde_json and are still rejected by Rust; if symmetric strictness there is wanted, optionally add a range guard in clankerprof/compare.py _summary_total (reject value < -(2**63) or value > 2**64 - 1) — not required for this defect. Add a parity/unit test comparing two reports whose summary.total_time_ns is 18446744073709551614 (and u64::MAX) asserting exit 0 and byte-identical compare artifacts in both languages, e.g. alongside the existing compare cases in tests/test_clankerprof_rust_parity.py.

