G11.fix_sketch:
Define the semantics once — "a library regex that declares capture groups names the library with group 1; if group 1 does not participate in a match, the pattern does not match" — and implement identically in both languages (skipping the pattern keeps byte parity trivially, and avoids the whole-match fallback whose relative_path computation differs between the languages today).

Python (clankerprof/patterns.py, replace lines 216-224):
    if match:
        if match.groups():
            component = match.group(1)
            if component is None:
                continue  # declared group did not participate: pattern names no library
            relative_path = normalized[match.start(1):]
        else:
            component = match.group(0)
            relative_path = component
        return LibraryPath(
            name=_normalize_library_component(component, rules),
            relative_path=relative_path,
        )
    continue

Rust (crates/clankerprof-core/src/targets.rs, replace lines 305-308):
    let whole_match = captures.get(0)?;
    let component_match = if regex.captures_len() > 1 {
        match captures.get(1) {
            Some(group) => group,
            None => continue, // declared group did not participate
        }
    } else {
        whole_match
    };
    let component = component_match.as_str();
    let relative_path = normalized[component_match.start()..].to_string();

(regex::Regex::captures_len() counts group 0, so >1 mirrors Python's non-empty match.groups().) Net effect on the repro: both implementations exit 0 and emit NO unattributed library for /gems/bar/file.rb — this changes Rust's current output, which is acceptable because Python is the reference and Rust's "gems/bar" (slash-embedded name from the whole match) was an accident of the unwrap_or fallback. Accompany with: a unit test in both languages (non-participating optional group → extract_library_path returns None; participating group still extracts "foo"), a parity-suite rule pack case in tests/test_clankerprof_rust_parity.py, one sentence in docs/CLANKERPROF_SPEC.md's rule-pack section defining the group-1 semantics, and the docs/CLANKERPROF_PARITY.md matrix note per CLAUDE.md's "Python and Rust together" rule.
